%I A393910 #39 Apr 06 2026 18:59:23
%S A393910 7,307,491,441953,26349353,55419011,2519515811,150952678787
%N A393910 Smallest prime p for which, for every i with 1 <= i <= n, the numbers p - i and p + i have the same number of divisors.
%e A393910 a(1) = 7, because for i = 1 to 1, the divisor counts of the symmetric pairs 7 - i and 7 + i are [4], respectively.
%e A393910 a(2) = 307, because for i = 1 to 2, the divisor counts of the symmetric pairs 307 - i and 307 + i are [12, 4], respectively.
%e A393910 a(3) = 491, because for i = 1 to 3, the divisor counts of the symmetric pairs 491 - i and 491 + i are [12, 4, 8], respectively.
%e A393910 a(4) = 441953, because for i = 1 to 4, the divisor counts of the symmetric pairs 441953 - i and 441953 + i are [24, 8, 12, 4], respectively.
%e A393910 a(5) = 26349353, because for i = 1 to 5, the divisor counts of the symmetric pairs 26349353 - i and 26349353 + i are [32, 8, 24, 16, 24], respectively.
%e A393910 And no smaller prime exhibits this symmetry.
%o A393910 (PARI) isok(n, p) = for (i=1, n, if (numdiv(p-i) != numdiv(p+i), return(0))); 1;
%o A393910 a(n) = my(p=2); while (!isok(n, p), p=nextprime(p+1)); p; \\ _Michel Marcus_, Mar 02 2026
